WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.060
 Now let's talk about browser events.

00:00:02.060 --> 00:00:05.280
 We've been talking about events all along.

00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:07.360
 We have done an onClick handler, which

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:11.360
 is a shortcut to, in effect, register a click event handler,

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:13.720
 but we're just doing it with the shortcut of the onClick

00:00:13.720 --> 00:00:14.680
 attribute.

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:16.520
 And then when we do a setTimeout,

00:00:16.520 --> 00:00:19.660
 we're actually creating a timer event.

00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:21.860
 So the timer starts, and then when the timer expires,

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:24.220
 the event fires, and our code is run.

00:00:24.220 --> 00:00:26.600
 So we've been doing this all along.

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:30.080
 But there is an entire event registration system inside

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:30.900
 the browser.

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:35.800
 And we can say, I would like to register an event for something

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:37.320
 to happen on this tag.

00:00:37.320 --> 00:00:40.120
 And we can hook things in all over the place.

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:43.640
 And there's a separate event registration system.

00:00:43.640 --> 00:00:49.260
 onClick is like a shortcut using an attribute that eventually

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:50.840
 registers the event on our behalf.

00:00:50.840 --> 00:00:52.640
 And that's why you see the little event when

00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:54.040
 you do the inspect element.

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:57.400
 And so if we take a look at the code here,

00:00:57.400 --> 00:00:59.400
 we're going to do the same thing that we

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:02.080
 did in 03event.htm, which we've seen before.

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:06.240
 And then we're going to do it again in 10-event.htm.

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:10.720
 And we're going to show the more generic way of doing it.

00:01:10.720 --> 00:01:14.800
 So in 03event.htm, we have an onClick method.

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:15.920
 We've done this before.

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:19.100
 And it calls my func when that method is clicked.

00:01:19.100 --> 00:01:20.480
 And if you do an inspect element,

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:25.320
 you see that that anchor tag has an event on it.

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:29.180
 The kind of more pure way to do it,

00:01:29.180 --> 00:01:31.560
 where we're really explicitly registering the event,

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:34.920
 these two things are front-ends and purposes equivalent,

00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:38.080
 is we're going to, instead of having the onClick method

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:40.600
 on the anchor tag, we're going to have an id equals zap.

00:01:40.600 --> 00:01:43.920
 And again, we have to put the id on so we can get our hands on it

00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:46.040
 inside JavaScript.

00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:50.960
 So we create an h1 and a paragraph with an anchor tag in it.

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:52.360
 Then we start our JavaScript.

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.520
 And the JavaScript starts by defining a function.

00:01:54.520 --> 00:01:55.720
 It doesn't do anything.

00:01:55.720 --> 00:01:57.200
 It just defines the function.

00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:01.320
 And then we call document.getElementByIdZap.

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:04.800
 Now, that is grabbing that anchor tag.

00:02:04.800 --> 00:02:09.440
 And then it calls an element method called addEventListener.

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:11.240
 And it's got two parameters.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:14.360
 The first parameter is I'm interested in the click event.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.360
 I want to listen for click events.

00:02:17.360 --> 00:02:21.040
 And when click events happen, call my func.

00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:23.240
 Now, again, first class functions,

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:24.800
 there's no parentheses on my func.

00:02:24.800 --> 00:02:28.080
 That is a function reference that we defined three lines

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.400
 earlier, right?

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:32.400
 And so it accomplishes the same thing.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:35.440
 And if we look at 10event.htm and we take a look at it,

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:38.480
 you see that the anchor tag with the id of zap

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:41.680
 doesn't have an onClick on it, but it has a registered event.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:46.440
 And that's because we registered the event using JavaScript.

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.080
 Now, if we click on it, it does the exact same thing.

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:50.680
 That event is triggered.

00:02:50.680 --> 00:02:52.840
 It looks up and says, well, when a click happens,

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:54.120
 I'm supposed to call my func.

00:02:54.120 --> 00:02:58.240
 And so this notion of adding event listeners

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:02.840
 is a more general purpose notion than simply onClick.

00:03:02.840 --> 00:03:06.240
 I like to think of onClick as a shortcut to registering it.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:09.760
 Now, you might say it's a lot shorter.

00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:12.680
 And one thing about JavaScript is it's a bit wordy at times,

00:03:12.680 --> 00:03:13.560
 right?

00:03:13.560 --> 00:03:17.520
 document.getitementbyid.addEventListener,

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:18.320
 a lot of JavaScript.

00:03:18.320 --> 00:03:22.120
 But it does what you need it to do.

00:03:22.120 --> 00:03:25.520
 And I'm not saying you shouldn't use onClick,

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:28.880
 but I want to show you the more general way of doing it.

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:33.120
 There are other kinds of events that we can connect to.

00:03:33.120 --> 00:03:36.320
 And so in this case, I'm going to just have

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:38.160
 a header and no paragraph.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:39.600
 And then in my JavaScript, I'm going

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:41.480
 to create a function.

00:03:41.480 --> 00:03:44.800
 And in that function, I'm going to log the current height

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:47.640
 and width of the window.

00:03:47.640 --> 00:03:50.880
 When this function is called, it's only going to log it.

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:54.880
 Now, what I'm going to say is window.addEventListener.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:57.200
 Now, remember, document.addEventListener,

00:03:57.200 --> 00:03:58.800
 that's a different thing, right?

00:03:58.800 --> 00:04:03.120
 Window.addEventListener is adding an event to the window.

00:04:03.120 --> 00:04:04.880
 Remember how the window is the thing

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:08.600
 that gets larger and smaller and has scroll bars, et cetera.

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:12.320
 So I'm saying I would like to register a bit of my code

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:16.720
 to be called every time the window is resized.

00:04:16.720 --> 00:04:18.640
 That's what quote resized quote is.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.800
 My func is to think to call.

00:04:20.800 --> 00:04:23.880
 So now what happens is you display this,

00:04:23.880 --> 00:04:26.600
 and then you start changing the size of the window.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:29.960
 And on your console log, it's zoom, you know?

00:04:29.960 --> 00:04:32.680
 Window height, 135, 136, 137.

00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:37.000
 So as you're making that window larger and smaller,

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.000
 your code is being called every time.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.400
 Now, why might you want to do this?

00:04:41.400 --> 00:04:44.320
 Well, one of the big things in website design

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:46.280
 is to do what's called responsive design.

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:49.400
 And that's as the thing gets narrower, or higher,

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:52.200
 or smaller, like mobile.

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:53.800
 You want to change the UI.

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:55.480
 You might have-- on a big screen,

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:57.000
 you might have a more complex UI.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:58.580
 And then on a small screen, you might

00:04:58.580 --> 00:05:01.000
 want to have a more narrow UI.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.080
 Now, often things like Bootstrap take care of all this for us.

00:05:05.080 --> 00:05:07.960
 But still, Bootstrap needs to get their hands

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:10.560
 on the resize event so they know, whoa,

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:11.680
 the screen size changed.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:14.600
 So I need to kind of tweak the markup a little bit.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:17.480
 So this is an example of a window event that

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:21.800
 allows you to render an opinion as to what you want to happen

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:23.920
 every time the screen resizes.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:27.920
 Now, another issue that's an important event to know about

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:32.020
 is what's called the content load complete event.

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:34.760
 Modern web pages are very, very complex.

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:36.400
 I mean, the things I've been showing you

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:38.800
 in this series of lectures are simple,

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:41.860
 because I want you to be able to see them on a slide.

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:45.320
 But real web pages with menus, and pretty pictures,

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:47.880
 and colors, and spinners, all that stuff, right?

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:49.000
 There's so many things.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:50.360
 You've got to download the HTML.

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:52.360
 Then you've got a bunch of CSS, and some images,

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:53.880
 and JavaScript libraries.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:57.800
 And so sometimes, you're going to just get like 100 assets

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:59.220
 when you download a page.

00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:01.720
 The first one is the HTML.

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:04.000
 And so the problem is, is it can take a while

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.920
 for all these things to get orchestrated by the browser.

00:06:06.920 --> 00:06:08.000
 It reads the HTML.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:09.080
 It sees the CSS.

00:06:09.080 --> 00:06:10.280
 It loads the CSS.

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:11.880
 It sees the JavaScript thing.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:12.840
 Loads the JavaScript.

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:13.720
 It da-da-da-da.

00:06:13.720 --> 00:06:16.040
 And then it's got some images, and it takes some time.

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:20.200
 And it does this all interleaved, and in parallel.

00:06:20.200 --> 00:06:22.440
 And eventually, you want to know, are you done yet?

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:24.160
 Or just, are you done?

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:27.520
 And so if we take a look at a typical page of Django

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:33.600
 for Everybody, we see about 30 requests, and many requests.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:36.200
 And you'd like to know when that's all done.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:39.480
 Because you can't write JavaScript

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:42.080
 that references a tag that doesn't exist yet.

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:44.840
 Or if you want to write JavaScript

00:06:44.840 --> 00:06:47.160
 that does something to an image, like changes its size

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:49.720
 or checks something, or hides it or shows it,

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:52.040
 you've got to wait till the image is there before you start

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:53.700
 messing with it, right?

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:55.600
 So there is a special event.

00:06:55.600 --> 00:06:56.600
 It's pretty simple.

00:06:56.600 --> 00:07:01.280
 And in this, you use a script tag near the end of your body.

00:07:01.280 --> 00:07:06.040
 So we have a function, myfunk.

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:09.920
 And in that function, the console log, the DOM is landed.

00:07:09.920 --> 00:07:12.040
 And then we're going to add event listener.

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:14.640
 And this is a document event, because this

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:16.000
 is DOM content loaded.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:17.520
 Not window, but DOM content.

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:19.280
 Document add event listener.

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:21.680
 The event name is DOM content loaded.

00:07:21.680 --> 00:07:23.520
 That's a hard-coded string.

00:07:23.520 --> 00:07:25.520
 And I say, please call my function

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:29.160
 when all the files have been loaded, and we're ready.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:31.400
 And the user can see the page.

00:07:31.400 --> 00:07:33.160
 And so in this one, it's really short.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:36.760
 It's just that console, the myfunk

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:39.320
 happens after the content is loaded,

00:07:39.320 --> 00:07:42.560
 and after all the derivative things have been loaded,

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:45.200
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

